      "createdAt": "2026-03-25T21:53:37.490589+00:00",
      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "James, please don't apologize. It takes real courage to say this out loud, and the fact that you're telling me now — that matters. A lot of people in your position would just quietly stop showing up. You didn't.\n\nI also want to be honest with you: I can hear that you've been carrying this alone for a bit, and that's a heavy thing to do.\n\n---\n\nNow, I have to be straight with you about something important. **Diagnosing what's happening with your foot and telling you how to treat it — that's genuinely outside what I can do for you.** I'm your running coach, not a medical professional, and plantar fasciitis that's worsening through continued running is exactly the kind of thing that deserves a proper clinical eye. Guessing wrong here could mean a much longer road back.\n\n**What I'd encourage you to do right now:** Contact your physiotherapist — the one who cleared you — and let them know what you've just told me. That the pain has been increasing, that you've had to stop mid-run three times, and that you're concerned it may have gotten worse. They need that full picture to help you properly.\n\n---\n\nHere's what I *can* tell you, from a coaching standpoint: **we're pausing all running until you've spoken with your physio.** Not as a punishment — as the smartest move available to us right now. Every day we protect that foot is a day we're investing in the comeback, not losing it.\n\nAnd when you come back with guidance from your physio — whatever that looks like — we'll build from exactly where you are. There's a clear path forward here. We just need the right information to walk it.\n\nWhat's your relationship like with your physio — is reaching out to them something you can do in the next day or two?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_01NEUCVuHPBrVgCYd9xKd9LK"
    }
  ],
